$$source: 8.02 Lecture 4
$$title: Electrostatic Potential
$$use-outline: true

*<m>U</m> = Electrostatic Potential Energy
	<m>W = \int_\infty^R \vec{F_{push}} \cdot \vec{dr} = \int^\infty_R \vec{F_{el}} \cdot \vec{dr}</m>
		because forces are in opposite directions
	<m>W = \frac{q_1 q_2}{4 \pi \epsilon_0} \int^\infty_R \frac{dr}{r^2}</m>
		<m>\int^\infty_R \frac{dr}{r^2} = \frac{1}{R}</m>
	*<m>U = \frac{q_1 q_2}{4 \pi \epsilon_0 R}</m>
		sign-sensitive w.r.t. charges
	

*<m>V</m> = Electric Potential
	Work per unit charge to go from infinity to this location
	<m>V_p = \frac{Q}{4 \pi \epsilon_0 R}</m>
	J / C = Volts
	
	<m>V = \int_r^\infty \frac{\vec{F_{el}}}{g} \cdot \vec{dr} = \int_r^\infty \vec{E} \cdot \vec{dr}</m>
		
	<m>W = \Delta Vq</m>
			
	Potential inside hollow metal sphere is constant = same as surface
	
	*Equipotential lines
		Field lines always perpendicular
		Never intersect
		
	With multiple charges, add potential for all
	
	*Potential Difference
		<m>V_A = \int_A^\infty \vec{E} \cdot \vec{dl}</m>
		<m>V_B = \int_B^\infty \vec{E} \cdot \vec{dl}</m>
		<m>V_A - V_B \int_A^B \vec{E} \cdot \vec{dl}</m>
	
